Insightful. I write magical realism, but am often force to market it as urban fantasy. And because my characters are realistic from various walks of life -- a high school jock, a union iron worker, a professional musician, a janitor, a bartender, a high school teacher, etc. --  I get the inevitable comparison to Stephen King. But my idea is to sniff around how Americans mistreat the underclass, and have since the 80&#039;s. So my demons are all some form of &quot;Free Market&quot; sociopath. And how those demons prey on people&#039;s frailty, 

Like you point out, genre&#039;s a gray area, but the difference between magial realism and urban fantasy is there if you read enough.

FYI. Gabriel García Márquez won the Nobel Prize for literature, not the book &#039;100 Years of Solitude.&#039; The Nobel is not like the National Book Award, rewarding an extraordinary work, but instead rewards an author&#039;s entire body of work. Which includes the excellent &#039;100 Years of Solitude.&#039;
